                <div class="penno-avobilam-container1">
                    <h1 class="penno-avobilam-heading mt-2">Lepakshi Veerabhadra Temple</h1>
                    <p class="penno-avobilam-description">Lepakshi Veerabhadra Temple, located in Anantapur district of Andhra Pradesh, has a rich historical significance dating back to the 16th century. It was built during the Vijayanagara Empire by the brothers Virupanna and Viranna, who were devout followers of Lord Veerabhadra. The temple showcases stunning architecture and intricate carvings depicting mythological scenes and deities. It is renowned for its suspended pillar, known as the "Aakaasa Sthambha," which hangs without any support. The temple also features a colossal monolithic Nandi (bull) statue, carved out of a single granite rock. Lepakshi Veerabhadra Temple holds cultural and religious importance and is a popular pilgrimage site. It stands as a testament to the artistic grandeur and architectural brilliance of the Vijayanagara era.
                    </p>
